tip.text: For a unique angle on Rio de Janeiro's hotspots, head to the rooftop infinity pool at the Philippe Starck-designed Hotel Fasano.
During the spring and summer, DJs create a lounge atmosphere. Cocktails and light dishes by the hotel's culinary director, chef José Andrés, top off the experience. Rooms start at $349 a night.

formattedAddress: 465 S La Cienega Blvd (at Clifton Way)

tip.text: Venice's only rooftop hotel pool offers a 360-degree view of the unique cityscape, with Piazza San Marco in the distance.
From the majesty of Lake Ontario to the architecture of the CN Tower, guests at the hotel can see it all. The hotel's infinity pool and rooftop lounge are open to hotel guests and lounge members.
A dip in the Marina Bay Sands' 150-meter infinity pool, touted as the world's largest for its height, comes with a truly stunning Singapore view.
Green is the name of the game here, from hemp-blend mattresses to a fleet of electric Teslas. Even the key cards are made of recycled wood.
This new Marriott outpost is buzzing with energy everywhere you turn, from the rooftop pool and happening AC Lounge to the on-site pop-up shops and other communal areas.
Open since late May, Aloft's first-ever resort-style property offers South Beach chic without the puffed-up price tag.
Right in the middle of central Beirut city is a poignant reminder of the country's past conflict. It's been the centerpiece for historically significant milestones in Lebanon's history.
It's an oasis of calm in an otherwise chaotic city with large green spaces and panoramic views of the coast.
It's located in the Badero district, once a sleepy residential area and now a buzzing favorite. Not only a place for a cocktail but also a chess battleground among locals.
The vibe is casual -- a huge marquee over the open kitchen lists the daily oyster menu in bold black letters, and vinyl booths line the street-facing windows. But the menu is classy.
Night owls will dig La Sandwicherie's extended hours. The stand is open until 5 a.m. during the week, 6 a.m. on Fridays and Saturdays.
The legend goes it was Weiss who first served stone crabs claws, now a delicacy on menus throughout Florida.
Diners can munch on guava pastries and croquettes while eavesdropping on discussions about U.S. relations with Cuba and the state of Fidel Castro's health.
Yardbird is especially popular for its chicken and waffles, served with a side of spiced watermelon and bourbon maple syrup.
If you're a fan of discovering local artists -- and great mojito -- while traveling, Ball & Chain offers some of the best music the city has to offer.
Our favorite was the simple but delicious chicharrones, tender pieces of pork belly fried to salty perfection.
The biggest draw comes from the accompanying gardens -- a carefully cultivated subtropical paradise.
It serves some of the best empanadas in town. Stuffed with cumin seasoned ground beef flecked with raisins and olives, they're best eaten with a cup of cafe con leche.
Recommended dishes on its creative menu include the sea salt roasted fig, apple and crunchy leave salad or the beetroot hummus and mushroom cupcakes with ricotta cheese.
Menu stars include the crunchy posto narkel bora (roasted fritters made with coconut and poppy seeds) and the bhekti paturi (fish wrapped and cooked in ripe banana leaves).
Chow down on a thick sloppy joe, Frito and tater tot chili or a classic Double-Wide burger before enjoying a Moon Pie for dessert.

contact.facebookName: 'the original' TRAILER PARK LOUNGE & GRILL, NEW YORK CITY

tip.text: The Connaught Hotel's signature bar is a triple threat: it's got killer cocktails, a prime London address and is an architectural marvel.
Downtown is packed with shiny business hotels, but the leader of the pack has to be the Four Seasons Hotel San Francisco.
It's well worth spending the night. The castle's historic rooms have been beautifully restored as hotel facilities.
You could be fooled into thinking this sleek rooftop bar is in Midtown Manhattan -- if it weren't for the views of the snow-capped Andes.
What to drink: Its signature Veruschka, a mix of pomegranate juice and sparkling Italian wine, said to be Princess Diana's favorite when visiting here.
Guests ride a special cable car down a dramatic cliff face to arrive at the brilliantly engineered Rock Bar, perched 46 feet above the Indian Ocean.

venue.name: Ayana Resort and SPA_ Jimbaran BALI

tip.text: Picture New York's High Line with a riverfront -- Crescent Park is a 1.4-mile recreational corridor bordering the Mississippi that includes a fenced dog run, picnic areas, and hike and bike trails.
A recent addition to the museum is the Road to Berlin: European Theater Galleries, which illustrates the struggles to defeat the Axis of power through historic artifacts and period newsreels.
Once a long-abandoned space occupied by Gators Department store, this is now the New Orleans Jazz Market, new home to Grammy winner Irvin Mayfield and his New Orleans Jazz Orchestra.
This 188-room Starwood property in the Central Business District boasts, among other features, a rooftop pool and a lounge complete with pool table.
There's only one safe and legal way to get to the icy lake: Cleetwood Cove Trail, a 1.1-mile (one-way) trail that usually opens in June and drops nearly 700 feet to the lake shore.
The plains are the only known place in the world where visitors can dig for selenite crystals with hourglass-shaped "inclusions." Geology geeks will love the experience.
For the full experience of the 80- to 100-foot dune, try kiteboarding or sandboarding, which are allowed by permit during parts of the year in a designated area. .
Watch large numbers of bats fly out of Carlsbad Cavern, the park's namesake cave, every evening around sunset from mid-April or May through late October or early November.
Visit the park's Hubbard Rhino Barn to see the fossils preserved as they died and to watch excavations being carried out in front of you. Rhino and tortoise are common finds.

venue.name: Ashfall Fossil Beds State Historical Park

tip.text: Winter snow is the perfect canvas for spotting animal tracks -- and possibly the animals themselves. You may see coyotes, lynx, moose, elk, beavers, snowshoe hares or even the elusive mountain lion.
You can picnic in the dunes, observe a large colony of gray seals and explore the rebuilt lighthouse, which was toppled by a storm in 1984. Stay through sunset, when the beach takes on a new mystery.

Chili crabs were invented at this Singaporean institution. The crabs are paired with a rich, spicy sambal with meat stock and lime. Just before plating, eggs are dropped in to the smooth the equation.

formattedAddress: Level 6. Novotel Clarke Quay (Liang Court) (177A River Valley Rd)

tip.text: The unique "double flavored beef soup," with both spicy and clear broths, is served in a yin-yang shaped bowl.

venue.name: Silks Palace at National Palace Museum (故宮晶華)

tip.text: Bowls here combine Japanese ramen broth with Chinese sliced noodles. Each order of its thick chewy noodles is carved off a big block of noodle dough.

venue.name: Taiwan Yi Pin Ramen And Sliced Noodle

tip.text: Loaded with thick tender slices of beef, the rich-flavor beef noodles here were made famous when local celebrity couple Chen Chienchou and Christine Fan served 600 bowls of it at their wedding.

formattedAddress: 忠孝東路五段10號12F (基隆路一段)

tip.text: Yong Kang Beef Noodles, made with Sichuan-style spicy red broth, include Australian beef as the main cuts. We recommend the beef noodle and tendon soup.

venue.name: Yong Kang Beef Noodle (永康牛肉麵)

tip.text: We recommend the New Formosa beef bowl at the Azie Grand Cafe. It features beef slices alongside bird's nest fern, a crunchy and slightly bitter green from Taiwan's mountains.
Apart from being one of the best restaurant's in Peru's capital city, it's achieved success with overseas restaurants in several countries, serving inventive Peruvian dishes like patada de res.
Tony Boy Escalante of Antonio's landed the country on the list of Asia's 50 Best Restaurants for the first time this year. One reason: Antonio's tempura oysters with mango orange sauce.
The Gowanus "Batcave" was the home of a thriving squatter community in the early 2000s. Today it's being renovated into artists' studios and an exhibition space.
Founded on 45 rpm records, not LPs, vinyl is still the bedrock of the inventory here. The store holds special sales on Record Store Day, when customers line up around the block.
Vinyl is king at Hymie's Vintage Records. People sometimes stop in to greet Irene, the store's Boston terrier, whose picture once appeared in a Rolling Stone article.
Founded in 1997, Jackpot Records is one of Portland Oregon's, leading sources of new and used vinyl. The store also operates an independent record label.
Vintage Vinyl was founded by two buddies in 1979 as a booth at a farmer's market. Today it's one of St. Louis' classic record stores, stocking everything from rock to gospel to reggae to Latin jazz.
Steve Earle, Lucinda Williams and many other celebrated artists have played gigs at Twist & Shout, this venerable Denver record store.
No trip to Austin is complete with out a visit to Waterloo Records, a landmark since 1982. The store has hosted appearances by everyone from Willie Nelson to Spoon.
After a day of visiting historic buildings, it's possible to spend the night at one. The Bussaco Palace is a hilltop castle commissioned as a romantic retreat by King Carlos I in 1888.
It may not look austere, but the medieval Alcobaça Monastery was meant to reflect the frugal lifestyle of the Cistercian monks who once inhabited it.
An incredible 50% of the holiday home is unsupported, but it's so solidly balanced that a swing has been installed at the end of it.
Founded in 1836, the Providence Athenaeum is an independent, member-supported library. The Greek Revival building that houses the library was designed by Philadelphia architect William Strickland.
Brimming with legal volumes, the Iowa State Law Library is located on the second floor of the Capitol Building. The library's tile floor and stained glass ceiling date to 1884.
Half-domes bookend either end of an impressive barrel-arched ceiling in Boston Public Library's Bates Hall. The 1895 library on Copley Square was designed by Charles Follen McKim.
The Stephan A. Schwarzman Building of the NYPL is a Beaux Arts landmark. Designed by the firm Carrère & Hastings, the library opened to the public in 1911. It houses about 15 million items.
Seattle's $166 million Central Library opened in 2004. Designed by Rem Koolhaas and Joshua Ramus, the building contains 9,994 pieces of exterior glass with 4,644 tons of steel.
Designed by Rob Wellington Quigley, the $185 million San Diego Central Library opened in 2013. The library has a three-story domed reading room and 350-seat auditorium.
Built between 1902 and 1906, the library features towering triple tiers of bookcases made of bronze and inlaid Circassian walnut. J.P. Morgan Jr. gave his father's library to the public in 1924.
Designed by Moshe Safdie, the library opened in 2003. A six-story curving wall hugs a central daylgiht-filled plaza, and a rooftop garden offers sweeping views of the Utah's Salt Lake Valley.
Find alligators by walking or cycling the 15-mile, looped trail. And if you don't feel like walking or biking, two-hour tram tours are a popular back up. Be sure to give the gators plenty of space.
This peninsula is accessible only by foot, as its reserve status doesn't allow for motorized vehicles on land. Not to worry: it's only four miles, round trip, and suitable for novice hikers.
The 37-acre search field, which sits on top of a volcanic pipe, is the only public site in the world where you can dig for diamonds to your heart's content.
Take a sea kayaking trip at Bartlett Cove to get a closer look at the icy phenomena. If you're lucky, you'll see a moose or bear swimming across the bay.
Rafters and kayakers will find some of the best white water in the South. But beware: They don't call the most harrowing stretch "the Suicide Section" for nothing. These are expert-level rapids.
The banh mis, or "Vietnamese po-boys," can't be missed. A can of coffee and bean pastry on your way out are a good supplement to an already satisfying meal.
One can avoid Parkway's line (Barack Obama ate there, so now everyone does) by calling ahead to place their order at the bar. The surf and turf po-boy is a must-try.
Though some muffulettas are served cold, at Cochon Butcher the bread is toasted and the meats are warm, held together with a generous spread of house-made, slightly briny and bright olive salad.
Believed to be the boundary between the spirit and human worlds, the Otorii's vermilion color is said to keep evil spirits away. You can walk to it on the sand bar during low tide.
It steals some of the attention from Kumano Nachi Taishai, a sacred shrine built close by. And it's usually the last stop of the scenic pilgrimage known as Kumano Kodo.

formattedAddress: 東牟婁郡那智勝浦町, 和歌山県

tip.text: Walking into an oil painting? The fragrant wisteria tunnel, the most stunning display at the Kawachi Fuji Garden, makes it possible.
Landing at this tiny strip clinging to the coast of Madeira will have you reaching for the fortified wine.

venue.name: Cristiano Ronaldo Madeira International Airport (FNC) (Aeroporto Internacional da Madeira Cristiano Ronaldo)

tip.text: Touching down at this strip in northeast Norway can feel like landing on an ice rink.
If there were awards for beautiful airport surroundings, Paro, in Bhutan, would have a shelf full of trophies.
For some, landing at this James Bond ("Tomorrow Never Dies") stunt scene provides an even bigger buzz than the local skiing.
The beach-skimming landing approach at this Caribbean airport has people gnawing their fingers in the plane and on the ground.

contact.facebookName: Princess Juliana International Airport - St. Maarten

venue.name: Princess Juliana International Airport (SXM) (Internationale Luchthaven Prinses Juliana)

tip.text: At 1,140 meters, Bampo Moonlight Rainbow Fountain in Seoul is the world's longest bridge fountain. It takes water directly from the Han River and has 380 jets.

venue.name: Banpo Bridge Moonlight Rainbow Fountain (반포대교 달빛무지개분수)

tip.text: At Fantawild, the chairoplane is less chair, more plane, lofting startled passengers up to almost cruising altitude in a creaking chair that turns wildly on it's own axis.
Not only are you sitting in a soda-can shaped car, the soda can coaster plays fast and loose with physics by flinging you in such tight loops you can almost see the back of your own head.
Though not open to the public, the owners do give the occasional tour of this colorful curiosity. Evidently a man-made accident, this odd formation spews geothermally heated water.
Red Beach gets its name from seaweed that flourishes in the saline-alkali soil. The plant turns vibrant red in the fall.
The oranges, pinks and purples of Antelope Canyon are amplified and muted by the changing sunlight filtering down from above, with the most intense colors emerging during the summer months,
The largest hot spring in Yellowstone, Grand Prismatic Spring is about 300 feet across and 165 feet deep. The spring's psychedelic look is caused by algae producing orange, yellow and red pigments.

Beautifully striped rock formations define the Danxia Landform near Zhangye in China's Gansu province. The rich, earthy colors are the result of sandstone and minerals deposited millions of years ago.
An eruption of algae brings a predominantly blood red color to the river when the water levels are right. Guides offer tours of the area, which is part of the national park Sierra de La Macarena.
The remote lake is accessible via plane or boat excursion from nearby Esperance. The cause of Lake Hillier's color isn't fully known. Salinity and bacteria are two possible sources of the unique hue.
London's oldest pie and mash shop opened its doors in 1892. Plus, it's down the road from Tower Bridge, one of London's most picturesque landmarks. Eat pie, than gaze down into the Thames.
This shop, a new one done in the old style, is part of a growing number of "pie and mash plus" places that offer chicken and mushroom, steak and kidney and vegetarian as well as minced beef.
Located on the bustling Kowloon waterfront, the plush inner-city InterContinental Hong Kong proves that amazing private plunge pools aren't exclusive to breezy island resorts.

venue.name: InterContinental Hong Kong (香港洲際酒店)

tip.text: With an 18-hole golf course designed by Pete Dye, two infinity pools and just 26 suites, La Reunión is a true luxury escape.
A cliff-side location, dramatic Piton vistas and luxe, tree-house-style suites make for a winning trifecta at this St. Lucia institution.

The rustic resort, set in the rugged cliffs of Puerto Rico's northwest coast, has 20 elegant, freestanding casitas outfitted with an expansive wooden deck,  outdoor dining area and marble plunge pool.
Though this stylish resort is built around a spectacular negative-edge pool, six of Amangiri's suites come with their own desert-facing infinity pools for added luxury.
Each villa has a private infinity pool overlooking the Aegean Sea. Book the Diamond Villa, where your oversize ocean-view pool is built into a sumptuous outdoor living room.
Curtains shield the loft-style Cobbler from the street, but brush past these and you'll find a spectacular drink library downstairs, and an upstairs room featuring graffiti on walls and sofas.
Pass through an unassuming doorway with just a small sign hinting that something grander might exist behind it. Enter the Walrus: a storeroom-cum-speakeasy with it's own house-spiced rum.
Upstairs is the door to the washroom. Push the wrong door, however, and you'll end up in the Mermaid Bar, another bar with a pirate theme, hidden within Lefty's.
Highlights include the world's largest exhibition of potato-related farm machinery and the world's largest potato sculpture.
You can expect a Deep South welcome at this museum. Visitors are allowed to eat and drink while touring the exhibits, which are focused on the cultures and traditions behind Southern cuisine.
The museum -- like the nation -- takes kimchi seriously. There's even a library filled with reference books and academic papers dedicated to the pickled product.
The city of York was built on chocolate. At York's Chocolate Story Factory Zone, it's possible to watch master chocolatiers in action before the all-important taste test.
Gouda, Edam, Leerdammer, Leydon, Maaslander, Maasdam. They're not just cities in the Netherlands, they're different types of cheese -- all of which can be learned about at this Dutch museum.
Each region in Japan has its own version of udon noodles. The museums highlights 35 of them.

formattedAddress: 京都市東山区, 京都府

tip.text: Check out exhibitions exploring the history of the world's most popular food, with lots of opportunities to try some yourself.
Check out exhibits like the history of ramen or a replica of the first ramen dish ever eaten. The consumer was 17th century samurai named Mito Komon.

venue.name: Shin-Yokohama Ramen Museum (新横浜ラーメン博物館)

tip.text: Check out the incredibly well stocked gift shop, though you run the risk of never wanting to see a Colman's Mustard product ever again by the end of the visit.
The hotel's timber-wrapped cubist blocks overlook the Atlantic, whose massive winter swells are wildly popular with surfers and storm watchers.
The brainchild of Sam and Georgie Pearman, this Regency building has 13 bedrooms, elegantly done with reclaimed-wood tables, freestanding Victorian bathtubs and David Hockney prints.
Book a Samezen massage, which uses warm stones and plant extracts, then take in the mountain views from a natural hot-spring-fed pool.
Residents of the Bolivian city of El Alto no longer have to brave the gridlocked road leading to La Paz below. Every hour 11,000 passengers make the seven-mile journey, paying 44 cents each.
This urban gondola connects Roosevelt Island with the Upper East Side of Manhattan. More than 26 million people have taken the three-minute journey since the tram opened in 1976.
Each winter, 1 million people use the 5-mile frozen stretch of the canal that passes through the center of Ottawa. Shelters, chalets and access ramps are installed to ensure the safety of commuters.
Explore the snowy mountains, otherworldly forests and breezy coast at Olympic National Park, and you'll find three different climates packed into one park.
No need to worry about crowds in winter. While the North Rim at the Arizona park closes, the icy South Rim stays open year-round. Take a ride on the Grand Canyon Railway if you prefer to stay warm.
Enjoy ranger-led snowshoe hikes or explore the 10 miles of the Going-to-the-Sun Road that the park service maintains in winter.
Cuyahoga Valley National Park offers winter sports courses at its outdoor center, operates a scenic railroad and hosts full-moon hikes throughout the winter.
Bryce Canyon National Park knows how to celebrate winter, with a winter festival held over Presidents Day weekend in February and  ranger-led snowshoe hikes from November through March.
More than 30 merchants offer a variety of produce, fresh meat and fish and specialty products seven days a week. It also hosts a seasonal farmers market on Saturdays and flea market in the summer.

Unlike regular street food, Lumpia Shack's plating is restaurant quality: the lumpia are arranged artfully on a tray, drizzled with homemade sauce and garnished with pea shoots and pickled vegetables.
New Yorkers don't need to go to New England for a good lobster roll. Thanks to Big Red, Red Hook Lobster Pound's lobster shack on wheels, they only need to walk to the curb.
Want to deep dive back into your favorite TV shows and movies of the 1960s and 1970s? Check into the Shagadellic Suite, the Genie's bottle or the Partridge Nest at this funky Catskills motel.
Want a taste of Tony Soprano's last supper? Order the onion rings for the table, just like Tony did, enjoy Journey's "Don't Stop Believin'" and say a prayer for late actor James Gandolfini.
Check out the facility's food tours offering tastes of Cajun cuisine and culture. Come with an appetite. The tours are three hours long, and reservations are recommended.
Head over on Sunday afternoons for a bingo game unlike any you've ever played at your local senior center. At this Austin saloon, Chicken Shit Bingo requires very little of your attention.

formattedAddress: 5434 Burnet Rd (btwn Shoalmont Dr & Lawnmont Ave)

tip.text: A genuine (former) Minuteman missile base, the kind of place from which America could destroy the world. Take a tour! The site is open from May through September.

venue.name: Ronald Reagan Minuteman Missle State Historic Site - November 33

tip.text: The terrace at this fine dining venue in the AO Building serves some of the best Sunday brunches in Tokyo and great cocktails. The Bloody Mary is fiery and full of flavor; the secret's in the sauce.
It's hard to remember you're sitting above arid desert while flicking through the wine list, considering Cuban tapas, taking in the Latin atmosphere.
The perfect spot to admire the São Paulo skyline and indulge in Brazil's most famous cocktail, the caipirinha. Come night, DJs entertain an international crowd.
The vibe is Stussy not stuffy -- exactly the laid-back oasis you were hoping to find when you fought L.A.'s bitter highway wars to get to this timeless pocket of SoCal beach culture.

venue.name: High Rooftop Bar at Hotel Erwin

tip.text: With panoramic views of the Indian Ocean along Umhlanga Beach, this is a top spot for romantics, shutterbugs and those who just like to sit, sip and smile.

venue.name: The Lighthouse Bar, The Oyster Box Hotel, Umhlanga

tip.text: There's a retractable roof, but no heaters, so only the hardy venture onto the terrace after the autumn chill sets in.
It's best to visit the outdoor deck before sunset to enjoy the skyline by the soft light of dusk. This way you can also avoid Sugar's garish pink and purple lighting that takes over once it's dark.

location.address: 32/F, EAST, Hong Kong, 29 Taikoo Shing Rd
formattedAddress: 32/F, EAST, Hong Kong, 29 Taikoo Shing Rd

tip.text: The draw here is an NYC vista you can gawk at from funky pastel chairs that seem to adapt to whatever shape is slouching in them. The staff lend out binoculars to ensure gazing is 100% operational.
To get a table you'll need to arrive early, but your efforts will be rewarded. If it's too cold, or you're too late, there's an indoor space with a glass wall so you can still see the view.

With gleaming skyline views, a glowing bar & more movers & shakers than a seaborne Yahtzee game, this rooftop bar promises good drinks, light snacks & a sense that the whole city is looking up at you.

formattedAddress: 13-14/F, The Peninsula Shanghai, 32 Zhongshan E-1 Rd (at E Beijing Rd)
location.address: 13-14/F, The Peninsula Shanghai, 32 Zhongshan E-1 Rd

tip.text: If you're looking for privacy, book one of Timara Lodge's four rooms. Plus, meals are paired with wine from the lodge's backyard winery or sizable.
Main beach is one of only two beaches in East Hampton where you can pay by the day for parking. Other town beaches require a village parking permit.
These 28 acres of gardens, greenhouses, walks & trails offer an oasis of serenity in the midst of NYC's concrete jungle. ProTip: Target sponsors free hours on Tuesday & Saturday mornings year-round.
This spa offers a Finnish-style body massage with fresh berry oil serum. Want to know how it got such a tropical name? Check out the bird at the front desk, then ask owner Ron Harrison for the story.

This spot bills itself as an adult playground, complete with tire swings, booths within pickup truck beds, and a tree-house bar. Game days come complete with rotating food trucks with delicious bites.
The Liege-Guillemin station in Liege, Belgium features an ultra-modern glass and steel facade. The wave-like ribbed roof suggests movement over the thousands of commuters that flow under it daily.
The Gare do Oriente in Lisbon is distinguished by its unique roof. The steel skeleton covers eight elevated tracks and their corresponding platforms, with the roof resembling the underside of a leaf.

formattedAddress: Av. D. João II (Av. de Berlim)

venue.name: Estação Ferroviária da Gare do Oriente

tip.text: The centerpiece of Netherlands' Rotterdam Centraal Station's design is the main entrance. The shiny boomerang-like canopy is made of a stainless steel projection and wood cladding.
The Hundertwasser Bahnhof train station in the northern German town of Uelzen was redecorated in 2000 by famous Austrian artist and architect Friedensreich Hundertwasser.

Built in 1859, Southern Cross station was renovated in '05 to include an undulating roof that covers an entire city block. At the western end of the station is a colorful "History of Transport" mural.
The upscale cuisine includes dishes like the Sean Connery (herb-buttered flame-broiled steak) and the Soviet Defector (beer-braised baby back ribs).
The trailer park vibe in this New York Bar and grill is unmistakeable. Try out their giant margarita's and a classic double-wide burger.

contact.facebookName: 'the original' TRAILER PARK LOUNGE & GRILL, NEW YORK CITY

tip.text: For over 30 years, this family-friendly restaurant on raised pillars over Mobile Bay has served seafood with a southern accent. Gulf oysters arrive on the half shell, either raw or chargrilled.
Eventide's Chinese-style steamed bun, filled with crispy fried oysters, tomato, and tart pickled daikon, red onion, and jalapeño, is a standout.
The menu is built around the company's three different oyster varieties, which vary in salinity and sweetness depending on where they're grown and proximity to the Atlantic Ocean.
Its famed oyster pan roast, with gently cooked Blue Points floating in a cream sauce with chile and paprika, is one of the longest-running menu items in New York City.
Wild Caper's Blades oysters from South Carolina are available at the raw bar; pickled shrimp or poached razor clams, served cold with an apple cilantro and jalapeño sauce, are another menu favorite.
A day trip to this bay-side shack is ideal during the warmer months of the year. Eaters are encouraged to shuck their own Shigokus and Kumamotos, but the store's employees will do it for a small fee.
Are oysters aphrodisiacs? This is the place to find out, as Island Creek happens to be one of America's most romantic restaurants.
This dive's specialty is Oysters Gilhooley, shucked on the half shell, dotted with butter and hot sauce, dusted with Parmesan cheese, and then wood-roasted until browned.
I've yet to see another spot in the South with such a thoughtful—and joyful—oyster program. The menu lists, give or take, 22 oyster varieties, most sourced from small family farms and flown in daily.

formattedAddress: 303 E Howard Ave (at N Candler St)

tip.text: The custardy bowl of scrambled eggs makes a decadent leap with briny, rich layers of uni (sea urchin): pureed, sliced, and whisked into hollandaise. As with anything, it boils down to the execution.
For his Tomato Galette, Matt envelops lemony ricotta in a toasted cornmeal crust, and piles on heirloom tomatoes—a twist on tomato pie without any pretension.
Mepkin Abbey oyster mushrooms join earthy kale and a runny Sea Island egg under Parmesan shards. Favas and peas sit atop ricotta made with John's Island milk, accented with sea salt from Bulls Bay.
Benton's bacon shows up in a bowl of mussels in a silken celery-fennel broth. The roasted whole trout bathes in wood smoke before joining a crisp potato-celeriac latke.

For anyone who loves a proper pig pickin', this is the tableside porcine dream. Wrap the smoky meat in fresh tortillas, pile on crunchy bits of skin, and top with radishes and roasted tomatillo salsa.

formattedAddress: 1530 Main St (btwn S Akard & Ervay St)

tip.text: The craft beer program is unparalleled in South Carolina, with 40-odd beers on tap, including a handful made in-house, and over 30 bottled options., and the cocktail program is relentlessly ambitious.
San Salvaje showcases chef Pyles' current obsession with Central and South American flavors, with perfect measures of ingenuity and restraint.
With the lamb shank, chef Ian Boden layers fresh (sweet green peas), rich (a crisp puck of meaty goodness), and creamy (a perfectly cooked runny egg) to produce a model of simple decadence.
The hotel is located near the Saigon River and close to all the action downtown. Restaurant options include Ming Court (Chinese) and Fuji (Japanese).
The area’s famous Communal Houses -- mini-temples that are mostly protected from the street by well-disguised entrances -- provide respite from the bustle.
The concept is simple yet ingenious. Much of the best food in Vietnam can be found on the streets -- the owners here have decided to serve local street staples in more upmarket surroundings.

venue.name: Quan An Ngon 18 Phan Boi Chau

tip.text: Appealing blend of Oriental charm and contemporary elegance. Major attractions include the setting near West Lake and lofty Summit Lounge bar on the hotel’s 20th floor.
You'll need to put up with crowds & walk at a slow pace to see all the exotic foods on display. On Saturdays, the Naschmarkt expands to include Europe’s largest flea market.
The Sofitel has a sophisticated bar that offers the absolute best view of the city. The floor-to-ceiling glass windows lay a glittering Vienna at your feet. No reservations allowed.
Albertina Passage is where the über-chic of Vienna go to dance. A major advantage is that there are a lot of seating nooks to sip your drinks in and get cozy with friends.

items.firstName: مطاعم لمسات مبهره للخروف الكامل المشوي على الجمر
items.lastName: مطاعم لمسات مبهره للخروف الكامل المشوي على الجمر

tip.text: Demel was the Imperial & Royal Court Confectionary Bakery to the former Austrian royal family. It produces exquisite cakes created by hand. You can check them out behind glass walls in the back.
Café Central is a coffeehouse first, but serves traditional Austrian food for lunch. The grand interior displays its palace setting to perfection, with a classical pianist serenading diners.

Plachutta is celebrated for its tafelspitz, the favored dish of Emperor Franz Josef. The boiled beef comes with a side of applesauce spiked with horseradish, which makes a sweet and spicy combination.
It uses fresh ingredients from the chef’s own farm & its location in the middle of a park offers a soothing escape from the bustle of the city. Open weekdays only.
The location is fantastic, right in the middle of Vienna’s biggest shopping street with an underground connection almost at the front door.
You can live like a prince at the Hotel Imperial. The building was originally constructed in 1863 as the Vienna residence of the Prince of Württemberg.
Murano has always been a secretive island, only a five-minute vaporetto ride from the center of Venice. Glassmaking traditions pass from father to son. Competition and copying are rampant.
Fresh vegetables and fruit from the local islands of San Erasmo and Vignole are on offer, as well as imports from the Mediterranean and beyond.
On the top floor, the store features a cool exhibition space. Vuitton has partnered with Venice's Civic Museums, to sponsor the restoration of classic artworks, which are loaned to this new space.

tip.text: Instead of being stuck on a crowded boat, you can ride on a comfy vaporetto, put in your earplugs & listen to a tour of the Grand Canal as you travel down one of the most spectacular water ways.
Outside there's a small square on the Grand Canal, and a little dock with a great view of the Rialto Bridge, where you can wander with your best-of-Venice drinks.
The fresh produce comes from San Erasmo, a local island in the lagoon; the fish comes from the Rialto market. Celsa makes the desserts by hand; the semifreddo alla meringa is a specialty.
The Bellini -- pureed white peache and prosecco -- was invented here, as well as the Carpaccio, created for an ailing countess ordered by her doctor to eat raw meat.
The focus is on fish that arrives daily from the Rialto market. The Laguna tasting menu includes Burrata cheese ravioli with mixed seafood, fresh tomatoes and oregano.
There are only 24 rooms for guests, plus two private gardens and a rooftop terrace -- making you feel like a privileged guest at a cozy, civilized house party that's been going on for centuries.
In December, you can trundle through the forest on the miniature train, enjoying myriad twinkling holiday lights at Stanley Park’s annual Bright Nights.
Not a typical visitor destination, Wreck Beach is difficult to access (you must hike down a forest path to reach the beach). Worth the hassle? Absolutely.
